segments.text: He got to be a general.
Was he a West Point man?
Oh yeah.
Most of you, okay, then all of your ROTC officers, the ones on active duty stationed here at A&M in the 30s, as far as you can remember, they were all West Point men.
I think it had been mighty unusual if they weren't.
None of them were originally from A&M?
Well I don't know about others and the other branches.
Of course we uh we had the different branches on campus and we didn't get very closely acquainted with people outside of our own branches and I'm sure that all of those that were associated
with us in the artillery branch for Westmoreland.
Okay.
Now tell me about these ROTC camps.
Well, we went to Camp Bullis, Texas outside of San Antonio.
Our other branches of ROTC went to other locations.
The duration was six weeks.
We lived a very spartan military existence.
We had long, demanding days.
We were supported by, in my particular camp,
C battery of the 12th Field Artillery, our horse-drawn outfit from Fort St. Houston.
We function directly under one of the sergeants and the battery.
Of course, we use their equipment, their horses, their artillery pieces, caissons, and all.
I'd say that it was quite a fine military training experience.
And you were also in this ROTC camp with other cadets from other colleges?
Yes, a few other colleges, not very many.
What colleges were they?
Oh gosh, it seems to me that we had some people from Oklahoma State University.
I don't remember others.
Nearly everyone there was a Texas A&M.
How'd you get along with these others?
Was it a rivalry?
Oh, well, I wouldn't say so beyond the rivalry you'd have when you're rotated into leadership positions of platoon sergeant or battery commander for a day or for an exercise or whatever.
but of course you didn't have any real authority, so you were dependent upon the cooperation of people.
There just weren't any reactionary people in ROTC in that time, so you got it right off just by having the cadet position, whatever it was.
support and loyalty pretty well just taken for granted.
What do you mean there weren't any reactionary people?
What do you mean by that?
Well of course we now see so prominently the draft resistors and activists of one kind or another from homosexuals to whatever it might be and of course those things just
weren't accepted during that period of time and there just wasn't any of it.
Right.
Everyone was there to do a job?
They were there to do a job.
Anybody that didn't conform usually didn't stay at Texas A&M very long.
So the people around Texas A&M at that time
We're all pretty much alike.
I won a card related to these things, which you occasionally find student complaints and uprisings on campus.
There's nearly always some kind of springtime cause that students get associated with.
Since everybody lived in military outfits,
if the leaders decided that we were going to protest something, there was a whole lot greater participation in protests than there would be now, dispersed.
I remember that in the spring of my senior year that there was an organized
protest, which was that the cleaners around the campus were going to raise the price for cleaning and pricing a pair of pants from 15 cents to 20 cents.
That was a major cause that we had, I think.
And did you have a lot of these causes?
I mean, did you have a lot of protests?
No, no, not very many.
I remember the leaders were
protesting.
Lauderstein was one of the cleaners then.
Youngblood, of course, they had student employees around each military outfit that would take up cleaning and pressing for them to take it in.
My gosh, the prices of the day, as you think about it,
They sure do seem low compared to now.
They sure would buy a lot, I know.
The meals in the dining hall, I believe our board bill was $21 a month.
Later reduced to $18 a month.
My goodness.
So that's about what you earned as a student laborer, so I guess the relationship between the earning power and what you can buy are about the same as today, but there wasn't much money around.
Now it appears that you feel that the Corps of Cadets then builds character.
Would you agree with that?
Oh, absolutely.
Well, I've heard that said many times before, and I always like to ask, well, what does that mean?
What does it mean that they build character?
Well, the expectations are fairly plainly expressed.
There is a discipline, and those that succeed conform
and accept the discipline, the relationship with others, the standards expressed.
To me, those things are part of character.
I think they shape a person's standards for living, not only in the military, but in other aspects too.
Do you think that the Corps had an impact on the fact that you became a leader?
Oh, certainly.
Could you explain?
Well, there is no question the reinforcement I would receive from these ROTC instructors that I admired so much
a little pat on the back here or there would inspire me to try to do better.

Here again, the tasks laid out, whatever they might be, there were certain standards, and if you performed up to the standards or exceeded them, you would be reinforced by recognition from the ROTC instructors.
It was very stimulating.
What were your feelings when the Corps was made voluntary in the 1960s?
I was 100% for it.
As a matter of fact, I was a member of the three-person study committee concerning compulsory ROTC and COIDS at Texas A&M.
Really?
Certainly.
The Corps had such an impact on your life.
Why would you not want to have the Corps part of every young man's life?
I would, but I wanted him to make the choice himself because the times had changed.
Even my own sons didn't choose to go through the ROTC program for Texas A&M.
Though they did enlist in Army Reserves and put in their careers that way,
Somehow the mood of the country and the young people had changed and I just don't believe in forcing people at that age to do something they don't accept.
That's really peripheral to the main purpose of Texas A&M and was more peripheral in the 60s than it was in the 30s.
That's a good point.
Often people or journalists, sometimes scholars, talk about a military mentality.
They put this in quotes.
Is there a military mentality, and if there is, could you explain it?
Well, there is a military mentality, I believe, but it's not the same today as it was in the 30s.
The military mentality changes, too.
There's no question that in the 30s, military officers had authority that was accepted, and that military command was authoritarian.
Because the young people that were in the services, or the older people too, had grown up in a disciplined environment and families, and they accepted authority.
That's certainly not true today.
There is much more democracy in military leadership.
It's essential that there be, and there is.
There is much more participation in decisions, and leadership is a lot harder today than it was in those days, where authority was just taken for granted and accepted.

I'd say that the military mentality is dominated by the fact that in a military organization, a person is expected to be willing to make the ultimate sacrifice to give up his life for whatever purpose he is committed to.
And that's a dominant thing.
You certainly have to be disciplined to do that in spite of being beset by all the fears and doubts that one has for a cause and upon demand by leaders that you respect.
You will accept great danger and sacrifice to the point of giving up your life for
your associates and for your country.
That's part of a military mentality.
And is that still believed?
Is that still believed today in your opinion?
That giving up your life?
I believe it is by a substantial portion of the population.
What about the military?
What about the population of the military?
Well, I think that this permeates the military, but I don't think that it does to the same degree that it is generally accepted as it was a few years ago.
I see.
that there are other motives for participating in the military.
I deplore the fact that we're trying to buy people and that compensation seems to be a dominant factor right now.
Because I don't believe that you get the same sort of a zeal and determination
same sort of performance, people that are motivated that way as they are just because basically.
By higher salaries, huh?
Yeah, by higher salaries or whatever, just because basically they are there during the time, during the period to protect the freedom of the country.
I sure believe everybody has an obligation to do that.
I would like to see every young person in the United States be called on to make some sacrifice to protect the freedom of the country.
Now that we're on this, would you include women in that?
Absolutely, I would now.
There's no question my attitude has changed over that time based upon my experience with women in the Armed Forces.
Well, could you describe that now that we're on this topic?
How has it changed?
Why did it change?
I was associated with some young women in the Army Reserve Organization.
They were just outstanding soldiers.
They performed mighty well in the tasks assigned to them.
Which type of tasks?
Well, in most cases these were administrative type of activities.
There were officers in?
Well, officers and non-commissioned officers.
My experience with the young women in the Army Reserves was quite favorable.
I'm sure that is a part of their equal rights that a very high proportion of the females in this country are willing to take up whatever sacrifices there might be.
It was a mighty big shock to me when I got into France and I found women that couldn't be trusted to actually, of course, ambush somewhere a soldier.
served as snipers.
That was a real shock to me that women would be combatants in some way like that.
Were these German women?
No, they were French women that had been associated with the German army and that really were supporters of the German people in one way or another.
And they were taking shots at you?
Oh, hell yes.
These women cleared down to the coast of France and all where we went in.
We learned pretty soon that my generation would trust women.
They would never think of it as that.
We learned pretty soon that you couldn't trust the women in that area.
Many of them had collaborated with the Germans.
had been, had accepted the Nazi cause and couldn't be trusted.
Of course, after the American army went through, the native French people dealt with them very harshly.
Shaved their heads and in some way identified those that collaborated with the Germans.
They were ostracized and worse,
But anyway, the Russians of course were using women during that period in their armed forces.
There was some in the German military, I guess some exposure along in World War II, in the combat phase.
And this changed your ideas in the 1930s.
That was the beginning of the change.
That started to change.
Then the primary thing that changed my attitude about women in the armed forces was in the Army Reserves,
I found them in a lot of the organizations.
I'd have to say that after the draft was released and we were recruiting under the voluntary army concept that we got more responsible people and women than we did men.
As a matter of fact, the standard for recruitment were higher.
Really?
Oh, sure.
Still are.
Still are.
It takes higher qualifications to enlist in the army or army reserves as far as I know today for females than it does for men.
Okay, I wasn't aware of that.
Oh yeah, well you have to make higher scores on the intelligence test to have a higher status.
Really?
Sure.
Doesn't that seem like discrimination?
Well it is.
Sure it is.
As far as I know, in the last three or four years, they haven't changed that.
We still have to make our scores.
You can't take them in category four on their intelligence status as you could men.
They've got to be more highly qualified.
So on the average, the ones we recruited during the Voluntary Army period were more intelligent, more responsible.
more dependable.
So I developed a lot of respect for young women in our forces.
You know, our sexual standards have changed a little bit, and we didn't worry so much.
First, we would have been mighty embarrassed to people my age
on the latrine facilities in the vicinity and that sort of thing, but that's just changed now.
As far as I know, in several years of experience, we didn't have any improper sexual incidents with women integrated into our military outfits.
Not any at all.
What were your ideas about women in the service back in the 1930s when you were here in the Corps?
Well, we never even considered it.
It wasn't even, well, that would be the farthest thing from our minds.
Nobody expected women to participate.
I guess the study during the time, two years I served on this committee, studying compulsory ROTC and coeds at A&M,
that I developed a little bit of an attitude then, because even then, for at West Point, women could go take graduate work.
It's a changing pattern in the country.
In other words, then you see A&M as a flexible institution.
Certainly.
And you see that as a positive aspect?
Certainly, certainly.
At that time, that was such an emotional question that the committee members' names were kept real.
secret and as far as I know it never even been revealed to this day but the integration of women in the Texas A&M proceeded exactly according to the recommendations of that committee.
Archie Flowers over at the College of Veteran Medicine was chairman of it.
Who else is on that committee?
Oh there's one gentleman and uh there were just three of us the other gentleman was in mechanical engineering I'll declare as
All right.
Getting back to the Corps, when you, in 1942, went into the military on active duty, what did you find was the opinion of other officers toward Texas A&M officers?
Well actually I went in in August of 1941 to serve a year.
But you went in April of 1942.
No, I got into the artillery in April of 1942, but I was already in the Army when it was the Pearl Harbor time.
Oh okay, then can you tell me, can you tell me, okay well we'll talk about that next, that you went in in 1941.
Let's talk, let's answer this first question now about the opinion of others when you went in in 1941 toward A&M officers.
Oh, the A&M officers had a fine reputation in the Army.
Well accepted.
Good performers.
They do today.
I'm very proud of that.
Even from the West Pointers?
Oh yes.
No snobbery or?
Well, not very much.
Of course,
There's always, there's no question during those days that the officers from the military academy had an age in being considered for promotions.
They deserved it.
Why do you say that?
Well, they were better.
You think a West Point graduate is better than an Aggie graduate?
I think for early performance,
In the Army?
Yes.
That's his whole purpose during four years and previous training.
Now, after two or three years, things even up, and the person can perform according to his own ability.
But there's no question in my mind that the training in the U.S. Military Academy
is better for a lieutenant to immediately perform in the active army than Texas A&M.
Sure.
Just by the nature of the military institution?
Well of course, that's what that's the, that's the whole purpose of it there, and they accomplished that purpose, but I don't think advantage lasts over two or three years.
You put the two people together and after two or three years,
A person from Texas A&M may be better qualified than a person from the U.S. Military Academy.
They will have gone to service schools.
They will have had experience.
Those things will have evened up the early advantage that the Military Academy person has.
There wasn't feelings that, well, you guys are just from A&M and we're from West Point or something?
You thought you were well accepted then?
Oh, no question.
I was right the first battery appointment I had was in the same military outfit that had served with us on ROTC camp.
I was in there with a young man named Smith, a fine officer from the military academy.
We were battery officers together.
There's no question we had mutual respect.
My god, he was a fine officer.
Didn't get promoted from second lieutenant to first lieutenant until his whole class got promoted.
It just happened that the second infantry division was an old line division.
They caddied to form three other divisions, but those of us that stayed with the division always said, well, they kept the best ones in the division.
They sent the worst ones out.
So anyhow, he was a second lieutenant just like I was and didn't get promoted until his whole class got promoted to old West Point class.
What about other ROTC officers from other institutions?
Most institutions at early 1940s had ROTC, of course, and what did what did they think of A&M, or how did you get along with those people?
Well, I'd have to say we had a superior attitude as commissioned officers in the Army about most
ROTC graduates.
We thought we were better than they were, and in a lot of cases we were.
However, there were many officers in my own artillery battalion from Oklahoma State University.
Actually, after a short time, I think we had an early advantage.
Just like I'd say that the Military Academy people let over us because of the emphasis on ROTC Texas A&M.
But I'd say that advantage would fade away in six months or something in the active Army.
We had fine, fine officers that obtained their ROTC commissions from Oklahoma State University.
Okay, let's talk about education here at A&M.
We've talked about the Corps for an hour or so.
Of course the main reason you were here was education.
Let's talk about education.
Who were instructors that had an influence on you?
Well here again I'd say that all of those that I had a great respect for the instructors that I was associated with.
the faculty members in the College of Agriculture Texas A&M had a genuine interest in their students at that time.
It was a very good association.
I'm proud that I think that still exists today.
Even with more students?
Oh sure.
I think our student-teacher ratio has not been altered all that much.
Sure.
But
D.W. Williams was head of the Animal Science Department, a gentleman who's still living today.
The baby's 88 years old.
Great respect for him, admired him, still do.
A.K.
Mikey, instructor in the Animal Science Department, who somehow took some special liking to me and got me associated with research early.
When I was a sophomore, he was working on beef, on meat tenderness research with Dr. Sylvia Culver, who's still alive today.
A.K.
Mackie died a couple years ago.
These were fine, fine people.
Gee, they would honor me by asking me to make trips with them sometime.
got me involved in academic activities that were carrying on.
I'm mighty proud of the people I was associated with in classes.
Dr. Charles N. Sheppardson was Dean of Agriculture.
Well, E.J.
Kyle was when I was a student, later Charles Sheppardson.
They were people to be admired.
